[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering class loaders and resources**\n\nI’m thinking about verifying both the directory and jar roots using URLClassLoader with a temporary directory that holds both the resource and the jar containing the manifest. I wonder about dynamic class loading with URLClassLoader since it loads classpath resources. But if the resource or jar is discovered after a native build, it might not work, especially in a native image setting. I should stick to the current test class loader instead, and maybe think about using a custom class loader for the native image.\n\n**Exploring dynamic class loading issues**\n\nI’m looking into the caveat of dynamic class loading for classes in jars discovered after the build. We may not need it, but just asserting not null might not provide enough coverage. I’m considering using the test’s own classloader with `asResourceFileSystem` to check metadata like `/META-INF/MANIFEST.MF`. This could fail if there's no manifest or root listings. Creating a test resource might help, but resources need configuration in native. I'm curious how this will all interact with the TCK agent involved.\n\n**Analyzing dynamic-access reports**\n\nI’m reflecting on the dynamic-access report, which has uncovered resource call sites. It looks like they expect tests to execute and record resource access, but that doesn’t indicate that metadata is missing. I might need to pull a test report to analyze class coverage effectively. Understanding that will help clarify the relationship between resource calls and their coverage during testing. It’s important I get this right for accurate results!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_03b7cd5c8bd989c40169f8db100f1481949b29e256cb36dd7a\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-NsegNnK5OTRFXPKM3icCM-I24EZj_0awUz02WT8S9T0eHjN4_P9UfmStJFO1BdFmLKuvrvotXc65xdX83j_yhZKVbrVWYjYUs-f2dUs8kNQ-p3XYS947XTZlMW8