e's the potential issue with `ClassLoader(null)` throwing a SecurityException—looks like that might not be a concern. \\n\\nI'm also contemplating if overriding `ClassLoader.getResources` in a Native Image could cause trouble with dynamic access calls. The agent likely records dynamic access based on stack traces, so if we don’t call `super.getResources`, the JDK API won’t execute, and no dynamic access will be recorded.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating ClassLoader instrumentations**\\n\\nSo, I'm looking at how the report frame indicates the call site line refers to the caller while tracking the API. If my override isn’t instrumented as `java.lang.ClassLoader#getResources`, then there won’t be coverage. I need to ensure that the actual `ClassLoader#getResources` is called, not just my override.\\n\\nIf I subclass and invoke `super.getResources(name)`, I believe that will access the API. It seems like this will actually invoke the API since the bytecode uses `invokespecial`. However, the stack frames will include both my override and `ResourceFileSystem`. I want to verify if the report attributes correctly based on the closest frame.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining call sites and stack traces**\\n\\nI'm noticing that the call to `ClassLoader` from `ResourceFileSystem` still uses the overridden method. The tracked API owner may not be straightforward. When I call `super`, the stack trace shows `ClassLoader.getResources <- RecordingResourceClassLoader.getResources <- ResourceFileSystem.toClasspathRoots`. \\n\\nIt sounds like the report frame may show `RecordingResourceClassLoader` as the caller instead of `ResourceFileSystem`. However, dynamic coverage tools probably track down to the library frame, so that’s manageable. I'm pondering whether the \\\"call site\\\" should indicate the line from `ResourceFileSystem`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering boot resources**\\n\\nI'm thinking about what boot resources could include. Would it be something for \\\"META-INF\\\"? Bootstrap might not be necessary. For another part, maybe it doesn't need to be included? Even if there are some resources, it seems that root mapping ignores non-file elements. But ultimately, I don’t think that matters too much. I should clarify my thoughts around this and see if there's a clearer point.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_23dmaVd7lNyl97CtoQ7FfWxF|fc_03b7cd5c8bd989c40169f8db7611448194a3de70df3a107641", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/com.squareup.okio/okio-jvm/3.0.0/src/test/kotlin/com_squareup_okio/okio_jvm/ResourceFileSystemInnerCompanionTest.kt", "edits": [{"oldText": "        override fun getResources(name: String): Enumeration<URL> {\n            requestedResourceNames += name\n            return Collections.emptyEnumeration()\n        }\n", "newText": "        override fun findResources(name: String): Enumeration<URL> {\n            requestedResourceNames += name\n            return Collections.emptyEnumeration()\n        }\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 800, "output": 1206, "cacheRead": 20480, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 22486, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777916773105, "responseId": "resp_03b7cd5c8bd989c40169f8db65b6508194a714e8b224fcdd75"}}
